SIMPLE: staff
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Staff
<hw>Staff</hw> <pr>(st⟦adot⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Staves</plw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧vz ⟦or⟧ st⟦aum⟧vz; 277)</pr> or
<plw>Staffs</plw> <pr>(st⟦adot⟧fs)</pr> in senses 1-9, <plw>Staffs</plw>
in senses 10, 11.</plu> <ety>[AS. <ets>staef</ets> a staff; akin to LG.
& D. <ets>staf</ets>, OFries. <ets>stef</ets>, G. <ets>stab</ets>, Icel.
<ets>stafr</ets>, Sw. <ets>staf</ets>, Dan. <ets>stav</ets>, Goth.
<ets>stabs</ets> element, rudiment, Skr. <ets>sth⟦amac⟧pay</ets> to
cause to stand, to place. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf. <er>Stab</er>,
<er>Stave</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A long piece of
wood; a stick; the long handle of an instrument or weapon; a pole or
stick, used for many purposes; <as>as, a surveyor's <ex>staff</ex>; the
<ex>staff</ex> of a spear or pike.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he put the <qex>staves</qex> into the rings on the sides of
the altar to bear it withal.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxviii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With forks and <qex>staves</qex> the felon to pursue.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stick carried in the hand for support or defense
by a person walking; hence, a support; that which props or
upholds.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Hooked <xex>staves</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The boy was the very <qex>staff</qex> of my age.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He spoke of it [beer] in ⟦ldquo⟧The Earnest Cry,⟦rdquo⟧ and
likewise in the ⟦ldquo⟧Scotch Drink,⟦rdquo⟧ as one of the
<qex>staffs</qex> of life which had been struck from the poor man's
hand.</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pole, stick, or wand borne as an ensign of
authority; a badge of office; <as>as, a constable's
<ex>staff</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methought this <qex>staff</qex>, mine office badge in court,⟦br⟧
Was broke in twain.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All his officers brake their <qex>staves</qex>; but at their
return new <qex>staves</qex> were delivered unto them.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A pole upon which a flag is supported and
displayed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The round of a ladder.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I ascended at one [ladder] of six hundred and thirty-nine
<qex>staves</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. J. Campbell (E. Brown's
Travels).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A series of verses so disposed that, when it is
concluded, the same order begins again; a stanza; a stave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cowley found out that no kind of <qex>staff</qex> is proper for an
heroic poem, as being all too lyrical.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The five lines and the spaces on
which music is written; -- formerly called
<altname>stave</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>An arbor, as of a wheel or a
pinion of a watch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The grooved director for the
gorget, or knife, used in cutting for stone in the bladder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <ety>[From <er>Staff</er>, 3, a badge of office.]</ety>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An establishment of officers in various
departments attached to an army, to a section of an army, or to the
commander of an army. The general's staff consists of those officers
about his person who are employed in carrying his commands into
execution. See <er>⟦Eacute⟧tat Major</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Hence: A body of assistants serving to carry into
effect the plans of a superintendent or manager; sometimes used for the
entire group of employees of an enterprise, excluding the top
management; <as>as, the <ex>staff</ex> of a newspaper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Jacob's staff</b></col> <fld>(Surv.)</fld>, <cd>a single
straight rod or staff, pointed and iron-shod at the bottom, for
penetrating the ground, and having a socket joint at the top, used,
instead of a tripod, for supporting a compass.</cd> -- <col><b>Staff
angle</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>a square rod of wood standing
flush with the wall on each of its sides, at the external angles of
plastering, to prevent their being damaged.</cd> -- <col><b>The staff of
life</b></col>, <cd>bread.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Bread is <xex>the staff of
life</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Swift.</au> -- <col><b>Staff tree</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>any plant of the genus <gen>Celastrus</gen>,
mostly climbing shrubs of the northern hemisphere. The American species
(<spn>Celastrus scandens</spn>) is commonly called
<stype>bittersweet</stype>. See 2d <er>Bittersweet</er>, 3
<sd>(b)</sd>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To set up one's staff</b></col>,
<col><b>To put up one's staff</b></col>, <col><b>To set down one's
staff</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To put down one's
staff</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to take up one's residence; to lodge.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Staff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Staff
<hw>Staff</hw> <pr>(st⟦adot⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.
<ets>staffiren</ets> to fill or fit out, adorn, fr. D.
<ets>stoffeeren</ets>, OF. <ets>estoffer</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧toffer</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>estoffe</ets> stuff, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧toffe</ets>. See <er>Stuff</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Plaster combined with fibrous and other
materials so as to be suitable for sculpture in relief or in the round,
or for forming flat plates or boards of considerable size which can be
nailed to framework to make the exterior of a larger structure, forming
joints which may afterward be repaired and concealed with fresh
plaster.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Staffier</ent>⟦br⟧
